<article id="post-706" class="post-706 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-core-classes-and-seminars tag-honors-seminar tag-leadership tag-speaker">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title">HON 401 Helps Bring Out the Leader in You</h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/hon-401-helps-bring-out-the-leader-in-you/" title="Permalink to HON 401 Helps Bring Out the Leader in You" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2014-05-05T20:59:33+00:00">May 5, 2014</time><time class="updated" datetime="2016-02-15T18:12:07+00:00">February 15, 2016</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/rpate243/" title="View all posts by rpate243">rpate243</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<div>
<div>
<p>Starting this spring, the Honors College introduced a new advanced Honors seminar—HON 401: Leadership, an extension of a previous seminar—that focuses on fostering leadership among Honors College students. Taught by Department of Managerial Studies Associate Professor Jenny Hoobler, the course guides students through leadership theory, research, and practice while attempting to uncover each student’s authentic leadership style. “I really want to get the point across to students that leaders come in all shapes, sizes, and variations,” says Professor Hoobler.</p>
<p>With guest speakers from organizations and businesses based in the Chicago area, students see first-hand how great leaders can be found in their own communities and are encouraged to tap into insights of leadership roles and perspectives. From leaders like Alderman Jason Ervin to the President and CEO of the Women’s Business Development Center Emilia Dimenco, the guest speakers fall nothing short of inspirational.</p>
<p>The three credit-hour course also gives students the time and opportunity to allow them to discover their own leadership potential. The class uses multi-factor leadership questionnaires to assess leadership potential and determine areas where students can improve. “I think it’s really important for students at this level to get that professional development and feedback,” states Professor Hoobler.</p>
<div id="attachment_707" style="width: 160px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-Shot-2014-06-25-at-9.00.43-PM.png"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-707" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-Shot-2014-06-25-at-9.00.43-PM.png" alt="Scott Dikkers, founding editor of The Onion, spoke to UIC students as part of the HON 401 Leadership Seminar." width="150" height="150" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Scott Dikkers, founding editor of The Onion, spoke to UIC students as part of the HON 401 Leadership Seminar.</p></div>
</div>
<div>
<p>Students’ professional development goes far beyond these assessments. Students also submit an article to a student academic journal of their choosing on a topic related to leadership towards the end of the semester.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<div>
<p>Professor Hoobler feels that her students are very interested and engaged in the class and adds that the chance for students to discuss their research questions is mutually beneficial. “That kind of environment where students are contributing and I’m sharing research that I really care about with them completely summarizes why I do this,” says Professor Hoobler. “It really gives me an intellectual charge to be able to do that. It’s the perfect environment for me, and I hope the students have benefitted from that as well.”</p>
<p>Professor Hoobler hopes to continue teaching this seminar, bringing in more community leaders who can inspire and help develop leaders among all Honors College students.</p>
<p><em>by: Francisca Corona, Sophomore, English</em></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
